ford|Jenny Sullivan]] {{small|(1989\u20132010; divorced)}}\n|children     = 4\n|profession  = Real Estate Developer<br />Politician\n|residence    = [[Sullivan's Island, South Carolina]] (1989\u20132010)<br>[[Charleston, South Carolina]] (2010\u2013present)\n|alma_mater   = [[Furman University]] <small>([[B.A.]])</small><br>[[University of Virginia Darden School of Business|University of Virginia]] <small>([[M.B.A.]])</small>\n|religion     = [[Episcopal Church (United States)|Episcopalian]]<ref>{{cite web | url = http://media.cq.com/members/436/rc=1 | title = Rep. Mark Sanford (R-S.C.) | work = Roll Call | publisher = CQ-Roll Call | accessdate = March 14, 2016}}</ref>\n|signature    = Mark Sanford signature.svg\n|website      = [http://sanford.house.gov/ Government website]\n|allegiance   = {{flagu|United States}}\n|branch       = {{Air force|United States}}\n|serviceyears = 2003\u20132013\n|rank         = [[File:US-O3 insignia.svg|15px]] [[Captain (United States)|Captain]]\n|unit         = [[315th Airlift Wing]]<br>315th Aeromedical Evacuation Squadron<br>[[Charleston Field]]<br>[[Air Force Reserve Command]]\n}}\n'''Marshall Clement''' \"'''Mark'''\" '''Sanford, Jr.''' (born May 28, 1960) is an American politician and member of the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]]. He currently serves as the [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] for [[South Carolina's 1st congressional district]] after winning a [[South Carolina's 1st congressional district special election, 2013|special election]] on May 7, 2013.<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.foxcarolina.com/story/22184869/sanford-colbert-busch-vie-for-congressional-seat | title = Sanford wins 1st District race, beating Colbert Busch | first = Casey | last = Vaughn | author2 = Associated Press | date =  May 7, 2013 | location = Charleston, SC | work = FOX Carolina | publisher = Meredith Corporation | accessdate = April 4, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | last = Sullivan | first = Sean | url = http://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/post-politics/wp/2013/04/02/mark-sanford-wins-republican-runoff-in-south-carolina/ | title = Mark Sanford wins Republican runoff in South Carolina | work = [[The Washington Post]] | date = April 4, 2013}}</ref> He previously represented the same district from 1995 to 2001, before being elected [[Governor of South Carolina]], a position he held from 2003 to 2011.\n\nFirst elected to Congress in 1994, Sanford pledged to serve no more than three terms and did not seek re-election in 2000. He left office in 2001 and was elected as the [[List of Governors of South Carolina|115th]] [[Governor of South Carolina]] in [[South Carolina gubernatorial election, 2002|2002]], defeating [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] incumbent [[Jim Hodges]], and was re-elected in [[South Carolina gubernatorial election, 2006|2006]]. As Governor, Sanford had a contentious relationship with the [[South Carolina General Assembly|South Carolina legislature]]: notably, he made public statements that he would reject [[stimulus (economic)|stimulus]] funds for his state from the [[American Recovery and Reinvestment Act of 2009]]. Following a subsequent battle in the [[South Carolina Supreme Court]], he was forced to accept the funds. In the House, he has been identified as a [[libertarian Republican]],<ref>http://www.fitsnews.com/2014/02/07/mark-sanford-growing-libertarian-footprint-in-congress/</ref> and was previously an ally of [[Ron Paul]] during their time in the House together.<ref>https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/post-politics/wp/2013/04/25/ron-paul-endorses-mark-sanford-2/</ref>\n\nOn June 24, 2009, Sanford publicly revealed that he had engaged in an [[Mark Sanford disappearance and extramarital affair|affair with Mar\u00eda Bel\u00e9n Chapur]], an [[Argentine]] woman.<ref name=\"postandcourier.com\">{{cite news | url = http://www.postandcourier.com/article/20140912/PC1603/140919776/1031/mark-sanford-and-maria-belen-chapur-call-off-engagement-blame-lingering-divorce | title = Mark Sanford and Maria Belen Chapur call off engagement, blame lingering divorce | work = The Post and Courier | date = September 12, 2014 | first = Schuyler | last = Kropf }}</ref><ref name=\"thestate.com\">{{cite news | url = http://www.thestate.com/2014/09/12/3677665/mark-sanford-breaks-up-with-fiance.html?sp=/99/205/&ihp=1 | title = Mark Sanford breaks up with fiance, blames ex-wife | work = The State | date = September 12, 2014 | first = Ali | last = Watkins }}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.nytimes.com/2009/06/27/us/27maria.html | work=The New York Times | title=Argentine Man Is Said to Be Source of Sanford E-Mail | first=Vinod | last=Sreeharsha | date=June 27, 2009 | accessdate=April 5, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://dyn.politico.com/printstory.cfm?uuid=22457D54-40D7-49A5-BA78-FD615E3299A1 |title=Mark Sanford faces family-values contrast in runoff |author=Isenstadt, Alex |date=March 20, 2013 |accessdate=March 25, 2013 |work=[[Politico]]}}</ref> While it led to [[censure]] by the [[South Carolina General Assembly]] and his resignation as chairman of the [[Republican Governors Association]], it did not result in Sanford's actual resignation from the governorship.\n\nSanford is also a [[real estate developer]] and a former medical administration officer in the [[Air Force Reserve Command|U.S. Air Force Reserve]].<ref>{{cite web| author = Associated Press |url=http://chronicle.augusta.com/stories/2003/02/26/met_376854.shtml | title = Members of governor's reserve unit called up | work = The Augusta Chronicle |date=2013-12-11 |accessdate=2014-08-08 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131211052624/http://chronicle.augusta.com/stories/2003/02/26/met_376854.shtml |archivedate=December 11, 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | work = Augusta Chronicle | url = http://old.chronicle.augusta.com/stories/2005/03/11/met_447018.shtml | title = Reservist Sanford is Transferred to Agency | date = March 11, 2005 | location = Charleston }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | publisher = ''[[The Post and Courier]]'' | work = The Island Packet | url = http://www.islandpacket.com/2013/05/03/2488752/questionnaire-mark-sanford.html | title = Questionnaire \u2013 Mark Sanford | date = May 3, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nMarshall Clement Sanford, Jr. was born in [[Fort Lauderdale, Florida]]. His parents were Marshall Clement Sanford, Sr., a [[cardiologist]], and his wife, the former Peggy Pitts. Despite his family being fairly well-to-do, his entire family slept in the same room to conserve electricity.<ref>{{cite web|author=Alt-Weekly Contributors |url=http://www.charlestoncitypaper.com/charleston/from-charleston-to-miami-los-angeles-to-boston-here-are-the-bottom-feeders-of-public-office/Content?oid=4948443 |title=From Charleston to Los Angeles, New York to Miami, here are the bottom feeders of public office &#124; Features |publisher=Charleston City Paper |date=2014-07-02 |accessdate=2014-08-08}}</ref> Before his senior year of high school, Sanford moved with his family from Fort Lauderdale to the {{convert|3000|acre|sing=on}} Coosaw Plantation near [[Beaufort, South Carolina]]. Sanford attained the rank of [[Eagle Scout (Boy Scouts of America)|Eagle Scout]] in the [[Boy Scouts of America]].<ref>{{cite news | url = http://chronicle.augusta.com/stories/030305/met_3495483.shtml | deadurl=yes | title = S.C. governor hears annual Scouting report from an Eagle | newspaper = The Augusta Chronicle | date = March 3, 2005}}{{dead link|date=November 2011}}</ref>\n\nSanford received a [[Bachelor of Arts]] degree in [[business]] from [[Furman University]] in 1983 and a [[Master of Business Administration]] degree from [[Darden Graduate School of Business Administration]] at the [[University of Virginia]] in 1988.<ref>[http://www.usnews.com/news/campaign-2008/articles/2008/05/22/10-things-you-didnt-know-about-mark-sanford 10 Things You Didn't Know About Mark Sanford] U.S. News & World Report</ref>  Shortly afterward, he moved to [[Sullivan's Island, South Carolina]], an affluent suburban community off Charleston.\n\nHe founded Norton and Sanford Real Estate Investment, a leasing and brokerage company, in 1992, and still owns the company.<ref>{{cite news | url = http://webcache.googleusercontent.com/search?q=cache:QZ_reuQn_UgJ:www.jhu.edu/clips/2002_10/14/sanford.html+%22Anti-Politics+Sanford+Stresses+Family,+Land%22&cd=1&hl=en&ct=clnk&gl=us&client=firefox-a | title = Anti-Politics Sanford Stresses Family, Land | first = Claudia | last = Smith Brinson | newspaper = [[The State (newspaper)|The State]] | date = October 13, 2002 | page = A1}}{{dead link|date=November 2011}}</ref>\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\n\n===Elections===\n[[File:Mark Sanford, Congressional photo.jpg|thumb|150px|left|Sanford in 1999]]\n;1994\nIn 1994, Sanford entered the Republican primary for the Charleston-based [[South Carolina's 1st congressional district|1st Congressional District]] in the [[United States House of Representatives]]. The seat had come open after four-term Republican incumbent [[Arthur Ravenel]] declined to seek re-election in his ultimately unsuccessful run for Governor. Despite having never run for office before, Sanford finished second in a crowded primary behind [[Van Hipp, Jr]], a former [[George H. W. Bush]] administration official and former Chairman of the [[South Carolina Republican Party]]. Sanford defeated Van Hipp in the runoff and easily defeated State Representative [[Robert A. Barber, Jr.]] in the [[United States House of Representatives elections, 1994#South Carolina|November general election]], winning by 66.3% to 32.4%.\n\n;1996\u20131998\nSanford was unopposed by Democratic candidates in 1996 and 1998. In [[United States House of Representatives elections, 1996#South Carolina|1996]], he beat Joseph Innella of the [[Natural Law Party (United States)|Natural Law Party]] by 96.36% to 3.55%. He beat Innella again in [[United States House of Representatives elections, 1998#South Carolina|1998]], this time by 91% to 8.9%.\n\n===Tenure===\nWhile in Congress, Sanford was recognized as its most fiscally conservative member by the [[Cato Institute]]. He was also recognized by Citizens Against Government Waste, as well as the National Tax Payers Union, for his efforts to rein in government spending and reduce the national deficit.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nationalreview.com/articles/337753/mark-sanford-i-m-running-congress-jim-geraghty# |title=Mark Sanford: I\u2019m Running for Congress \u2013 Jim Geraghty \u2013 National Review Online |publisher=Nationalreview.com |date=January 15, 2013 |accessdate=May 1, 2013}}</ref> He garnered a lifetime rating of 92 from the [[American Conservative Union]],.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.acuratings.org/ratingsarchive/1996/rhotex.html|title=1996 House Ratings|publisher=[[American Conservative Union]]|date=January 1, 1996|accessdate=June 24, 2009 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080612060738/http://www.acuratings.org/ratingsarchive/1996/rhotex.html |archivedate = June 12, 2008}}</ref>\n\nSanford was known for an independent streak. He was known for voting against bills that otherwise got unanimous support.<ref name=\"Newshour\">[https://web.archive.org/web/20130808034555/http://www.pbs.org/newshour/vote2002/races/sc_sanford.html Profile of Sanford] at ''[[PBS NewsHour|NewsHour]]''{{'}}s coverage of '02 governor's race</ref> For example, he voted against a bill that preserved sites linked to the [[Underground Railroad]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m1282/is_7_57/ai_n16372497/ |title=A Carolina kid: Republican governor Mark Sanford makes an impression |work=[[National Review]] |date=April 25, 2005 |author=[[John J. Miller (journalist)|John J. Miller]]}}</ref> He voted against [[pork barrel]] projects even when they benefited his own district; in 1997 he voted against a defense appropriations bill that included funds for Charleston's harbor. Seeing himself as a \"citizen-legislator\", he did not run for reelection in [[United States House of Representatives elections, 2000|2000]], in keeping with a promise to serve only three terms in the House.<ref name=\"Newshour\"/>\n\n===Legislation===\nDuring his first tenure in Congress, Sanford sponsored 39 bills, including:<ref>{{cite web|title=Representative Sanford's Legislation|url=http://www.congress.gov/member/mark-sanford/1012?q=%7B%22search%22%3A%5B%22Sanford%22%5D%2C%22sponsorship%22%3A%22sponsored%22%2C%22type%22%3A%22bills%22%2C%22congress%22%3A%5B%22106%22%2C%22105%22%2C104%5D%7D|publisher=Library of Congress|accessdate=December 12, 2014}}</ref>\n\n====104th Congress (1995\u20131996)====\n* H.R. 1104, a bill to allow states to set term limits on individuals for House and Senate seats from their respective state, introduced March 1, 1995\n* H.R. 2610, a bill to exclude members of Congress from participating in the [[Civil Service Retirement System]] and the [[Federal Employees Retirement System]], allowing instead for members of Congress to participate in the [[Thrift Savings Plan]], to require roll call votes (Yes/Yea or No/Nay) for votes relating to congressional pay, and to set limits on what circumstances members of Congress can use military transportation and military health care, introduced November 9, 1995, reintroduced in the 105th Congress as H.R. 436\n* H.R. 4319, a bill to require federal agencies to implement and maintain financial management systems that comply with federal laws and regulations, introduced September 28, 1996, reintroduced in the 105th Congress as H.R. 435\n\n====105th Congress (1997\u20131998)====\n* H.R. 2420, a bill to permit foreign-flag cruise vessels to transport Americans from one American port to another until an American cruise vessel takes its place, and to require such vessels to have repairs made in the United States, introduced September 5, 1997, reintroduced in the 106th Congress as H.R. 248\n* H.R. 2768, a bill to allow for a defined-contribution personal retirement account for employees similar to [[Individual retirement account]]s, introduced October 29, 1997, reintroduced in the 106th Congress as H.R. 249\n* H.R. 2782, a bill to gradually increase the Social Security retirement age and to reduce the annual percent change in the cost-of-living increase for Social Security, introduced October 30, 1997, reintroduced in the 106th Congress as H.R. 250 and H.R. 251\n* H.R. 4306, a bill to eliminate the spending cap adjustments for [[International Monetary Fund]] funding increases, introduced July 22, 1998\n\n====106th Congress (1999\u20132000)====\n* H.R. 1373, a bill to support the [[Yugoslavia#New states|former Yugoslav Republics]]' transition to democracy, to provide aid to regions and communities negatively affected by the Serbian government's actions during the [[Yugoslav Wars]], to impose sanctions on Yugoslavia, and to support the indictment of [[Slobodan Milo\u0161evi\u0107]] as a war criminal if the [[International Criminal Tribunal for the former Yugoslavia]] chooses to indict him, introduced April 12, 1999\n* H.R. 3516, a bill to prohibit [[Pelagic zone|pelagic]] [[longline fishing]] in the [[exclusive economic zone]] in the Atlantic Ocean, introduced November 22, 1999\n* H.R. 4471, a bill to allow U.S. citizens and legal residents to travel to and from Cuba, introduced May 16, 2000\n* H.R. 5349, a bill to allow individuals to have $3 on their tax return ($6 if filing a joint tax return) allocated specifically to reducing the federal government's public debt, introduced September 29, 2000\n* H.R. 5557, a bill to exempt from multi-family housing handicapped access design and construction (anti-discriminatory) requirements an individual dwelling unit that is readily convertible, and is so converted upon the request of a potential occupant, introduced October 25, 2000\n\n===Committee assignments===\n*'''[[United States House Committee on Foreign Affairs|Committee on International Relations]]'''<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2013-05-13/sanford-won-t-gain-plum-posts-in-return-to-u-s-house.html|title=Sanford Won\u2019t Gain Plum Posts in Return to U.S. House|publisher=Bloomberg|date=13 May 2013|accessdate=19 May 2013}}</ref>\n*'''[[United States House Committee on Oversight and Government Reform|Committee on Government Reform]]'''\n*'''[[United States House Committee on Science, Space and Technology|Committee on Science]]'''\n*'''[[United States Congress Joint Economic Committee|Joint Economic Committee]]'''\n\n==Governor of South Carolina==\n\n===2002 election===\nIn 2002, just before announcing he would run for governor, Sanford joined the Air Force Reserve. He entered the [[South Carolina gubernatorial election, 2002|gubernatorial election of 2002]]; he first defeated Lt. Gov. [[Bob Peeler]] in the Republican primary and then defeated the Democratic incumbent, [[Jim Hodges]], in the general election, by a margin of 53% to 47% to become the [[List of Governors of South Carolina|115th Governor]] of South Carolina. In accordance with South Carolina law, Sanford was elected separately from the state's Republican lieutenant governor, [[Andre Bauer]]. Sanford and Bauer's wins gave the Republicans full control of state government for the first time since [[Reconstruction Era|Reconstruction]].\n\n===First term===\nIn 2003, after becoming governor, Sanford attended two weeks of training with the [[U.S. Air Force Reserve|Air Force Reserve]] in [[Alabama]] with his unit, the 315th Aeromedical Evacuation Squadron. While in training in 2003, Sanford did not transfer power to Bauer, saying he would be in regular contact with his office, and would transfer authority in writing only if he were called to active duty.<ref name=\"Located-22Jun09\">{{cite news |work=The State |url=http://www.thestate.com/2009/06/23/836552/previous-coverage-sanford-back.html |date=June 22, 2009 |title=Sanford, missing since Thursday, reportedly located|author1=John O'Connor  |author2=Clif LeBlanc  |lastauthoramp=yes }}</ref>\n\nSanford sometimes had a contentious relationship with the [[South Carolina General Assembly]], even though it was dominated by his party for his entire tenure. The Republican-led [[South Carolina House of Representatives|state House of Representatives]] overrode 105 of Sanford's 106 budget vetoes on May 26, 2004.<ref name=\"overrides 2004\">{{cite web|author=Bauerlein, Valerie|title=S.C. House overrides 105 of 106 vetoes|url=http://www.thestate.com/mld/thestate/news/politics/8769969.htm|work=The State|location=Columbia, South Carolina|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040617141809/http://www.thestate.com/mld/thestate/news/politics/8769969.htm|archivedate=June 17, 2004}}</ref> The following day, Sanford brought live pigs, who subsequently defecated on the House floor, into the House chamber as a visual protest against \"[[pork barrel|pork projects]].\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wistv.com/global/Story.asp?s=1895905 |title=Gov. Sanford protests pork with pork at Statehouse Thurs. |publisher=WIS-TV |date=May 27, 2004|accessdate=May 8, 2013}}</ref>\n\nSanford rejected the Assembly's entire budget on June 13, 2006. Had this veto stood, the state government would have shut down on July 1. He explained his veto as being the only way to get the cuts he desired, and that using the line item veto would have been inadequate as well as impossible. However, in a special session the following day, both houses dismissed Sanford's call for reform by overriding his veto\u2013effectively restoring their original budget<ref>{{Cite news|title=South Carolina Showdown Is Set Up by a Budget Veto|url=http://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9406E0DD1031F936A25755C0A9609C8B63|date=June 15, 2006|accessdate=June 24, 2009|first=Brenda|last=Goodman|work=The New York Times}}</ref>\n\nSanford professed to be a firm supporter of limited government. Later in his tenure, he embarked on a plan to reform methods of funding the state's public education system, including measures such as [[school vouchers]]\u2013 aimed at introducing more competition into the school system as a means of fostering improvement. The plan, known as \"Put Parents In Charge\", proposed to provide around $2,500 per child to parents who chose to withdraw their children from the state's public school system and instead send them to independent schools. Sanford framed this plan as a necessary market-based reform.{{citation needed|date=August 2014}}\n\nIn 2003, Sanford sought to reform the state's public college system. Sanford has criticized these schools as focusing too much on separately creating research institutions and not on educating the young adults of South Carolina. Sanford also suggested that they combine some programs as a means of curbing tuition increases. The schools did not respond positively to this suggestion, however, causing Sanford to remark that \"if any institution ultimately feels uncomfortable with our push toward coordination, they can exit the system and go private.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Sanford urges privatization|url=http://chronicle.augusta.com/stories/2003/12/06/met_388896.shtml|work=The Augusta Chronicle|accessdate=May 8, 2013|date=December 6, 2003}}</ref>\n\nSanford also indicated a desire to increase the powers of the executive branch. Under the [[South Carolina Constitution]], the governor is somewhat weaker than many of his counterparts. For instance, many of his appointment powers are shared with the South Carolina General Assembly.\n\nSanford's first term included other controversies. A ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' magazine article in November 2005, critical of Sanford, said that some \"fear his thrift has brought the state's economy to a standstill.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,1129549,00.html |title=Mark Sanford / South Carolina |work=TIME magazine |date=November 13, 2005 |author=Tim Padgett}}</ref>\n\nAccording to [[Survey USA]], Sanford's approval ratings ranged from 47% to 55% during 2006.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.surveyusa.com/client/PollReport.aspx?g=8fb71556-8323-4a6a-b57f-b9698e6a1121 |title=Survey USA poll |publisher=Surveyusa.com |accessdate=July 25, 2012}}</ref> According to Survey USA, Sanford's approval ratings in South Carolina after his admission of infidelity (6-24-09) showed that \"60% think the Governor should resign. 34% feel he should remain in office.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.surveyusa.com/index.php/2009/06/25/south-carolina-60-think-governor-sanford-should-resign/ |title=Survey S.C. poll |publisher=Surveyusa.com |date=June 25, 2009 |accessdate=July 25, 2012}}</ref>\n\n===2006 election===\nHis campaign for [[South Carolina gubernatorial election, 2006|re-election in 2006]] began by Sanford winning the June 13 Republican Primary over [[Oscar Lovelace]], a family physician from [[Prosperity, South Carolina|Prosperity]], with 65% of the vote to Lovelace's 35%. His Democratic competitor in the November elections was [[South Carolina Senate|state senator]] [[Tommy Moore (politician)|Tommy Moore]], whom Sanford beat by 55%\u201345%.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/ELECTION/2006/pages/results/states/SC/G/00/ |title=\u2013 Elections 2006 |publisher=Cnn.com |accessdate=July 25, 2012}}</ref> Though ultimately, he left with a 55% approval rating.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2013/01/16/mark-sanford-congress-comeback/1838947/ |title=\u2013 Elections 2006 |publisher=usatoday.com |accessdate=January 26, 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn election day, Sanford was not allowed to vote in his home precinct because he did not have his voter registration card. He was obliged to go to a voter registration office to get a new registration card. \"I hope everybody else out there is as determined to vote as I was today\", he said. Sanford's driver's license had a [[Columbia, South Carolina|Columbia]] address, but Sanford was trying to vote at his home precinct in Sullivan's Island.<ref>{{cite web|agency=Associated Press|title=Sanford wins re-election|url=http://www.heraldonline.com/101/story/8824.html|work=The Herald|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061108162849/http://www.heraldonline.com/101/story/8824.html|archivedate=November 8, 2006|date=November 8, 2006|location=Rock Hill, South Carolina}}</ref> According to [[WAGT (TV)|WAGT]] in [[Augusta, Georgia]] (whose service area includes part of South Carolina) Sanford declared that it would be his last campaign.<ref>{{cite web|agency=Associated Press|url=http://www.nbc26news.com/news/local/4582991.html |title=South Carolina Governor Mark Sanford Not Allowed To Vote At His Home Precinct |work=NBC26news.com|date=November 7, 2006 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061122230253/http://www.nbc26news.com/news/local/4582991.html|archivedate=November 22, 2006}}</ref>\n\n===Second term===\nIn dissent with the Republican Party of South Carolina, Sanford, an [[Episcopal Church (United States)|Episcopalian]], {{citation needed|date=September 2014}} opposed the faith-based license plates his state offers, marketed largely to the state's [[conservative evangelical]] citizens. After allowing the law to pass without his signature, he wrote \"It is my personal view that the largest proclamation of one's faith ought to be in how one lives his life.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/blogs/politics/2008/06/gov-sanford-on/ |title=Gov. Sanford on the Podcast |publisher=Blogs.abcnews.com |date=June 5, 2008 |accessdate=July 25, 2012}}</ref>\n\nAfter the passage of the [[American Recovery and Reinvestment Act of 2009]], which Sanford strongly opposed and publicly criticized before and after its passage by [[United States Congress|Congress]] and presidential signing, Sanford initially indicated he might not accept all of the funds allotted by the spending law to South Carolina.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2009/feb/21/nation/na-mark-sanford21 |title=South Carolina's governor may turn down stimulus money |work=Los Angeles Times |date=February 21, 2009 |accessdate=July 25, 2012 |author=Fausset, Richard}}</ref> He was criticized by many [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrats]] and some moderate Republicans both in his state and outside who noted South Carolina's 9.5% unemployment rate (one of the highest in the country) and complained that Sanford wasn't doing enough to improve economic conditions in his state which he was intentionally trying to worsen, which could be alleviated by the stimulus money.<ref>{{cite web|last=Goodman |first=Josh |url=http://www.governing.com/blogs/politics/Should-Mark-Sanford-Reject.html |title=Should Mark Sanford Reject the Stimulus Money? |publisher=Ballotbox.governing.com |date=February 16, 2009 |accessdate=July 25, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.cnn.com/2009/POLITICS/02/16/begala.carolina/index.html |title=Commentary: If you oppose stimulus, don't take the money |publisher=CNN|date=February 16, 2009 |accessdate=July 25, 2012 |author=[[Paul Begala|Begala, Paul]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Davenport|first=Jim|title=Jobless benefits part of SC gov's stimulus blur|url=http://www.forbes.com/feeds/ap/2009/02/19/ap6071552.html|work=forbes.com|agency=Associated Press|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090222101428/http://www.forbes.com/feeds/ap/2009/02/19/ap6071552.html|archivedate=February 22, 2009|date=February 19, 2009}}</ref> [[Arnold Schwarzenegger]], the Republican [[Governor of California|Governor]] of [[California]], suggested that if Sanford or other governors rejected their portion of stimulus funds, he would be happy to take them instead.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.politico.com/news/stories/0209/19121.html |title=Arnold: I'll take govs' money |publisher=Politico.com |accessdate=July 25, 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn March 11, 2009, Sanford became the first United States governor to formally reject a portion of the federal stimulus money earmarked by Congress for the state of South Carolina.<ref>{{cite web|author1=James Rosen |author2=McClatchy Newspapers |url=http://www.mcclatchydc.com/2009/03/10/63706/south-carolinas-sanford-to-become.html#.UYE3L7Vtj4Y |title=South Carolina's Sanford to become first governor to reject funds |publisher=Mcclatchydc.com |accessdate=July 25, 2012}}</ref> Sanford compromised to accept the federal money on condition that the state legislature provide matching funds to pay down the South Carolina state debt.<ref>{{cite web|author=Andrew Romano |url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/newsweek/2009/04/24/last-of-the-true-believers.html |title=Mark Sanford: The Last Conservative Standing? \u2013 Newsweek and The Daily Beast |publisher=Newsweek.com |date=April 24, 2009 |accessdate=July 25, 2012}}</ref>\n\nSanford persuaded state legislator [[Nikki Haley]] to run as his successor, and campaigned on her behalf.<ref name=JRutenberg>{{cite news|last1=Rutenberg|first1=Jim|title=Mark Sanford's Path of Most Resistance|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2014/06/29/magazine/mark-sanfords-path-of-most-resistance.html|accessdate=30 June 2014|work=New York Times|date=26 June 2014}}</ref>\n\n====Rankings====\nThe [[Libertarianism|libertarian]] [[Cato Institute]] ranked Sanford as the best governor in America in their 2010 fiscal policy report card, describing him as \"a staunch supporter of spending restraint and pro-growth tax reforms\".<ref>[http://www.cato.org/pubs/pas/html/PA668/PA668index.html Fiscal Policy Report Card on America's Governors: 2010] Policy Analysis, No 668. Chris Edwards. September 30, 2010.</ref>\n\nIn its April 2010 report, Democratic-leaning watchdog group [[Citizens for Responsibility and Ethics in Washington]] <ref>{{cite web|author=Gordon, Greg|url=http://www.mcclatchydc.com/2006/10/13/14835/congressman-in-tight-race-for.html |title=Congressman in tight race for re-election comes under federal investigation|publisher= McClatchy Newspapers |accessdate=May 1, 2013}}</ref> named Sanford one of eleven worst governors in the United States because of various ethics issues throughout Sanford's term as governor and his time in Congress.<ref>{{Cite news | last = Vogel | first = Ed | title = Gibbons named on list of worst governors | newspaper = ''[[Las Vegas Review-Journal]]'' | pages = | date = April 21, 2010 | url = http://www.reviewjournal.com/news/gibbons-named-list-worst-governors | archiveurl = | archivedate = | accessdate =May 5, 2010 | postscript = <!--None--> }}</ref>\n\n==Disappearance and extramarital affair==\n{{Main article|Mark Sanford disappearance and extramarital affair}}\nFrom June 18 until June 24, 2009, the whereabouts of Sanford were unknown to the public, as well as to his wife and the State Law Enforcement Division, which provides security for him, garnering nationwide news coverage. The absence of Governor Sanford was first reported by [[Jim Davenport (journalist)|Jim Davenport]] of the [[Associated Press]].<ref name=politico>{{cite news |first=Dylan|last=Byers|title=AP's Jim Davenport dead at 54 |url=http://www.politico.com/blogs/media/2012/12/aps-jim-davenport-dead-at-153031.html |work= [[Politico.com]] |publisher= |date=December 31, 2012 |accessdate=January 15, 2013}}</ref><ref name=ap>{{cite news |first=Jeffrey|last=Collins|title=South Carolina AP reporter Jim Davenport dies |url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/south-carolina-ap-reporter-jim-davenport-dies |agency=Associated Press |publisher= |date=December 31, 2012 |accessdate=January 15, 2013}}</ref> [[Lieutenant governor (United States)|Lieutenant Governor]] [[Andr\u00e9 Bauer]] announced that he could not \"take lightly that his staff has not had communication with him for more than four days, and that no one, including his own family, knows his whereabouts.\"<ref name=\"Mystery-trip\">{{cite news |url=http://www.wistv.com/Global/story.asp?S=10574191|title=Governor gone for days; staff says he's hiking |date=June 23, 2009 |author=Davenport, Jim |work=WISTV.com |agency=Associated Press | accessdate=May 8, 2013}}</ref>\n\nBefore his disappearance, Sanford told his staff that he would be hiking on the [[Appalachian Trail]] and while he was gone he did not answer 15 cell phone calls from his chief of staff Scott English; he also failed to call his family on Father's Day.<ref>{{cite web|author1=Smith, Gina |author2=O'Connor, John |lastauthoramp=yes |date=July 14, 2009|url=http://www.thestate.com/154/story/862957.html|title=Sanford's office couldn't locate missing governor|work=The State|location=Columbia, South Carolina|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090903020234/http://www.thestate.com/154/story/862957.html?|archivedate=September 3, 2009}}</ref>\n\nReporter Gina Smith, of The (Columbia, S.C.) State newspaper, intercepted Sanford arriving at [[Hartsfield\u2013Jackson Atlanta International Airport]] on a flight from [[Argentina]]. Several hours later, after learning that incriminating evidence was being swiftly mobilized against him by the media, Sanford held a news conference, during which he admitted that he had been unfaithful to his wife.<ref name=\"wsj\">{{cite news|author= Alex Roth|author2=Valerie Bauerlein|title = Sanford Says He Had Extramarital Affair |url = http://online.wsj.com/article/SB124584667616347147.html|publisher = Wall Street Journal|location = Columbia, South Carolina|date=June 24, 2009|accessdate =June 24, 2009}}</ref><ref name=\"thestate\">{{cite web | work=[[The State (newspaper)|The State]] | url=http://www.thestate.com/2009/06/25/839231/sanford-admits-affair-ive-let.html | title=Sanford admits affair, wife Jenny responds | date=June 24, 2009 | accessdate=June 24, 2009 | last1=LeBlanc | first1=Clif | last2=O'Connor | first2=John}}</ref>\n\nIn emotional interviews with the [[Associated Press]] over two days, Sanford said he would die \"knowing that I had met my soul mate.\"<ref name=\"crossed lines\">{{cite news|author1=Lush, Tamara  |author2=Berland, Evan |lastauthoramp=yes |date=July 1, 2009|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/id/31664990/ns/politics-more_politics/t/sc-governor-crossed-lines-more-women/|title= S.C. governor \u2018crossed lines\u2019 with more women |work=NBCNews.com|agency=Associated Press}}</ref> Sanford also said that he \"crossed the lines\" with a handful of other women during 20 years of marriage, but not as far as he did with his mistress. \"There were a handful of instances wherein I crossed the lines I shouldn't have crossed as a married man, but never crossed the ultimate line\", he said.<ref name=\"crossed lines\"/>\n\nOn June 25, ''[[La Naci\u00f3n]]'', a [[Buenos Aires]] newspaper, identified the Argentine woman as Mar\u00eda Bel\u00e9n Chapur, a 43-year-old divorced mother of two with a university degree in [[international relations]] who lives in the city of [[Buenos Aires]].<ref>[http://www.foxnews.com/politics/2009/06/25/sanfords-mistress-identified-professional-passionate-beautiful-brunette/ ''Sanford's Mistress revealed as Professional, Passionate, Beautiful Brunette''], Fox News, June 25, 2009.</ref> ''[[The State (newspaper)|The State]]'' earlier had published details of e-mails between Sanford and a woman only identified as \"Maria.\"<ref>[http://www.thestate.com/2009/06/25/839350/exclusive-read-e-mails-between.html ''Exclusive, Read e-mails between Sanford, woman''], ''The State'', June 25, 2009.</ref> Sanford met Chapur at a dance in [[Uruguay]] in 2001 and admitted there was a more intimate relationship with her starting in 2008.<ref>{{cite news|title=Sanford admits additional encounters with Chapur, 'crossed lines' with other women|url=http://www.postandcourier.com/article/20090630/PC1602/306309958|work=The Post and Courier|author1=Lush, Tamara |author2=Berland, Evan |lastauthoramp=yes |agency=Associated Press|location=Charleston, South Carolina|date=June 30, 2009}}</ref>\n\nSanford's wife had become aware of her husband's infidelities around five months before the scandal broke, and the two had sought [[marriage counseling]].<ref name=\"thestate\" /> She said that she had requested a [[trial separation]] about two weeks before his disappearance.<ref name=\"boston news\">{{cite news | last=Davenport | first=Jim | url=http://hosted.ap.org/dynamic/stories/U/US_SC_GOVERNOR_WHERE?SITE=AP&SECTION=HOME&TEMPLATE=DEFAULT&CTIME=2009-06-22-17-10-09 | agency=Associated Press | title=SC gov with family as questions grow over absence \n| date=June 24, 2009|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090625174452/http://hosted.ap.org/dynamic/stories/U/US_SC_GOVERNOR_WHERE?SITE=AP&SECTION=HOME&TEMPLATE=DEFAULT&CTIME=2009-06-22-17-10-09|archivedate=June 25, 2009 }} Also published in ''The Boston Globe'' as: \"[http://www.boston.com/news/nation/articles/2009/06/24/sc_governor_who_took_hiking_trip_to_return_to_work/?page=full SC governor admits affair, secret Argentina trip]\"</ref>\n\nSanford told reporters that months before his affair became public he had sought counsel at a controversial religious organization called [[The Family (Christian political organization)|The Family]], of which he became a member when he was a Representative in Washington, D.C. from 1995 to 2001.<ref>Collins, Michael (July 10, 2009). [http://www.knoxnews.com/news/2009/jul/10/c-street-group-hurt-by-links-to-scandals/ \"Wamp, housemates hurt by links to scandals.\"] Knoxnews. Retrieved July 27, 2009.</ref>\n\nIn September 2014, Sanford and his ex-wife agreed on mediation over an argument arising from their divorce in 2010 after his extramarital affair while serving as the state's governor. Sanford's former wife asked the judge to require the congressman to undergo a psychiatric exam and take parenting and anger management classes. Judge Daniel Martin Jr. said he instead ordered them to take the issues to mediation within 30 days, as requested by a motion filed by the congressman.<ref>{{cite news|last1=McLeod|first1=Harriet|title=South Carolina congressman Sanford, ex-wife head to mediation|url=http://www.reuters.com/article/2014/09/15/us-usa-sanford-idUSKBN0HA1T320140915|agency=Reuters|accessdate=14 September 2014|date=September 15, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Fallout from scandal===\nHis wife, [[Jenny Sanford]], after telling ''[[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]]'' magazine that her husband was having a \"midlife crisis\", moved out of the [[South Carolina Governor's Mansion]], with the couple's four sons, returning to the family home on [[Sullivan's Island]].<ref>{{cite news|author=Sponsored by |url=http://www.economist.com/node/14367217 |title=The drive to replace South Carolina's governor is accelerating |publisher=Economist.com |date= September 3, 2009|accessdate=July 25, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Jenny Sanford, sons move out|url=http://www.thestate.com/local/story/893310.html|work=The State|author1=Burris, Roddie |author2=O'Connor, John  |lastauthoramp=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090811144710/http://www.thestate.com/local/story/893310.html|archivedate=August 11, 2009|date=August 8, 2009}}</ref> On December 11, 2009, she announced that she was filing for divorce, calling it a \"sad and painful process.\"<ref>{{cite news | url=http://edition.cnn.com/2009/POLITICS/12/11/sanford.divorce/ | title=S.C. governor's wife files for divorce | accessdate=December 11, 2009 | author=Hamby, Peter | date=December 11, 2009 | publisher=CNN}}</ref> The divorce was finalized in March 2010.<ref>{{cite news | title=Augusta businessman dating Jenny Sanford |date=April 14, 2010 |work=[[Augusta Chronicle]] |author=Pavey, Rob |id=2W6665906479}}</ref> A stipulation within his divorce papers demanded that while on the Sanford family's Coosaw plantation, \"no airplanes will be flown at children\". The papers also noted that Sanford liked to \"unwind\" by digging holes on the property with his hydraulic excavator.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wonkette.com/514340/mark-sanford-not-allowed-to-fly-airplanes-at-his-children-anymore |title=Mark Sanford Not Allowed To Fly Airplanes At His Children Anymore |publisher=Wonkette |date=2013-04-30 |accessdate=2014-08-08}}</ref>\n\nSanford posted lengthy remarks on his Facebook page on September 12, 2014, regarding his ex-wife's \"legal machinations surrounding the custody of their children\". His remarks on Facebook are longer than the total of all his 2014 speeches on the floor of the House of Representatives.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/the-fix/wp/2014/09/12/mark-sanfords-facebook-tribute-by-the-numbers/|title=Mark Sanford's Facebook novelette, by the numbers|author=Philip Bump|work=Washington Post|date=September 12, 2014}}</ref>\n\n====Resignation as Chairman of the RGA====\nSanford resigned as Chairman of the [[Republican Governors Association]],<ref>{{Cite news |first=Brian |last=Montopoli |title=Sanford Admits Extramarital Affair |url=http://www.cbsnews.com/8301-503544_162-5110133-503544.html |work= |publisher=[[CBS News]] |date=June 24, 2009 |accessdate=June 24, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.politico.com/blogs/politicolive/0609/Sanford_admits_affair.html | work=[[The Politico]] | title=Sanford admits affair | date=June 24, 2009 | accessdate=June 24, 2009}}</ref> and he was swiftly succeeded by [[Mississippi]] Governor [[Haley Barbour]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.politico.com/blogs/bensmith/0609/Barbour_takes_over_RGA.html | work=[[The Politico]] | title=Barbour takes over RGA | date=June 24, 2009 | accessdate=June 24, 2009}}</ref> In a June 29 email to members of his political action committee, Sanford said he had no intention of resigning as governor.<ref>{{Cite news |first=Peter |last=Hamby |title= Sanford contradicts himself on meetings with mistress |url=http://www.cnn.com/2009/POLITICS/06/30/sanford/ |work= |publisher=CNN |date=June 30, 2009 |accessdate=June 30, 2009}}</ref>\n\n====Reimbursement for his private use of public funds====\nAfter his affair was revealed in June 2009, Sanford first claimed, \"There's been a lot of speculation and innuendo on whether or not public moneys were used to advance my admitted unfaithfulness. To be very clear: no public money was ever used in connection with this.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2009/POLITICS/06/30/sanford/|title= S.C. Attorney General to review Sanford's travel records|publisher=CNN|date=June 30, 2009|first=Peter|last=Hamby\u2192}}</ref> After a reporter used the [[Freedom of Information Act (United States)|Freedom of Information Act]] to seek records of what public funds were used to pay for Sanford's trip to Argentina,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.politico.com/static/PPM130_redacted_travel.html |title=Documentation released by the South Carolina Department of Commerce in connection with taxpayer funds used to fund Sanford delegation expenses in Argentina |publisher=Politico.com |accessdate=July 25, 2012}}</ref> Sanford eventually chose to reimburse taxpayers for expenses he had incurred one year earlier with his mistress in Argentina.<ref>{{cite web|last=Vogel |first=Kenneth P. |url=http://dyn.politico.com/printstory.cfm?uuid=19217866-18FE-70B2-A8433E9A66883D89 |title=''Politico.com \"Sanford had trade mission rendezvous\" June 25, 2009 |publisher=Dyn.politico.com |date=June 26, 2009 |accessdate=July 25, 2012}}</ref> He said, \"I made a mistake while I was there in meeting with the woman who I was unfaithful to my wife with. That has raised some very legitimate concerns and questions, and as such I am going to reimburse the state for the full cost of the Argentina leg of this trip.\" On August 9, 2009, the AP reported that Sanford may have violated state law by other abusive use of state planes, including to fly to get a haircut.<ref>{{cite news|author=Davenport, Jim|title=AP Investigation: SC gov's plane use questioned|url=http://hosted.ap.org/dynamic/stories/U/US_SC_GOVERNOR_STATE_PLANE?SITE=AP&SECTION=HOME&TEMPLATE=DEFAULT&CTIME=2009-08-09-21-19-20|date=August 9, 2009|agency=Associated Press|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090812061539/http://hosted.ap.org/dynamic/stories/U/US_SC_GOVERNOR_STATE_PLANE?SITE=AP&SECTION=HOME&TEMPLATE=DEFAULT&CTIME=2009-08-09-21-19-20|archivedate=August 12, 2009}} Also published by CBS News as \"[http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2009/08/09/politics/main5228211.shtml \"Sanford Took Personal Trips on Plane]\".</ref>\n\n====Impeachment proceedings====\nOn August 25, state representatives [[Nathan Ballentine]] and [[Gary Simrill]] met with Sanford and warned him that the state legislature would impeach him if he did not resign. Ballentine, an ally of Sanford's, said afterward, \"I told him the writing is on the wall. ...he could put an end to it all, but if he doesn't, members of the House will take things into their hands.\" Sanford still declined to resign.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://politicalticker.blogs.cnn.com/2009/08/25/first-on-the-ticker-the-writing-is-on-the-wall-ally-tells-sanford/|title= First on the Ticker: 'The writing is on the wall,' ally tells Sanford|publisher=CNN|date=August 25, 2009|first=Peter|last=Hamby}}</ref>\nOn August 28, ''[[The Washington Times]]'' reported that Republican lawmakers in South Carolina were \"laying plans\" for a special legislative session on whether to impeach Sanford. Two bills of [[impeachment]] were being prepared, with bipartisan support in the state legislature.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2009/aug/28/sanford-future-in-hands-of-gop/|title= S.C. GOP to push for Sanford's removal|work=[[The Washington Times]]|date=August 28, 2009|first=Ralph Z.|last=Hallow}}</ref>\n\nOn October 23, 2009, two impeachment resolutions were introduced, but were blocked by Democrats in the South Carolina legislature.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://articles.latimes.com/2009/oct/28/nation/na-sanford-impeach28 | work=Los Angeles Times | title=Mark Sanford impeachment papers expected today | first=Richard | last=Fausset | date=October 28, 2009 | accessdate=May 12, 2010}}</ref> A month later, the resolution was successfully introduced and it was announced that an ''ad hoc'' committee would begin drafting articles of impeachment starting on November 24.<ref>{{cite news|last=Dewan|first=Shaila|title=Sanford Impeachment Considered|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2009/11/25/us/25sanford.html|work=New York Times|accessdate=May 8, 2013|date=November 25, 2009}}</ref> Meanwhile, the Ethics Commission formally charged Sanford with 37 violations.<ref>{{cite web|last=O'Connor |first=John |url=http://www.thestate.com/2009/11/20/1036200/ethics-panel-votes-to-charge-sanford.html |title=Ethics panel votes to charge Sanford \u2013 SC Politics |publisher=TheState.com |accessdate=July 25, 2012}}</ref> making his removal or resignation all that more likely.\n\nOn December 3, during its third public hearing on the matter, the ad hoc committee unanimously voted to remove the vast majority of charges from the investigation, stating that they didn't warrant \"overturning an election.\" On December 9, the committee voted 6\u20131 against impeachment, stating that the legislature had better things to do. However, the committee voted unanimously to censure the governor.<ref>{{cite web|last=O'Connor |first=John |url=http://www.thestate.com/2009/12/10/1063834/panel-votes-to-censure-sanford.html |title=Panel votes to censure Sanford, but against impeachment \u2013 SC Politics |publisher=TheState.com |date=December 10, 2009 |accessdate=July 25, 2012}}</ref> On the 16th the full House Judiciary Committee voted 15\u20136 to formally end the process.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thestate.com/2009/12/17/1074331/how-they-voted.html |title=How they voted \u2013 News Extras |publisher=TheState.com |accessdate=July 25, 2012}}</ref>\n\n=====Censure=====\nOn December 15, 2009, the House Judiciary Committee voted unanimously to censure Sanford. The full [[South Carolina House of Representatives]] voted 102\u201311 on the resolution in January 2010.<ref>{{cite web|last=Roth |first=Tanya |url=http://blogs.findlaw.com/celebrity_justice/2010/01/south-carolina-house-passes-censure-of-gov-mark-sanford.html |title=South Carolina House Passes Censure of Gov. Mark Sanford \u2013 Celebrity Divorce \u2013 Celebrity Justice |publisher=Blogs.findlaw.com |date=January 15, 2010 |accessdate=July 25, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Thrush |first=Glenn |url=http://www.politico.com/blogs/glennthrush/0110/South_Carolina_House_censures_Sanford.html |title=Full text of resolution |publisher=Politico.com |date=January 13, 2010 |accessdate=July 25, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Presidential elections==\n\n===Role in 2008 election===\nIn 2006, before the [[2006 midterm elections|midterm elections]], some commentators discussed the possibility of Sanford running for president.{{Citation needed|date=June 2009}} He said that he would not run, and claimed that his re-election bid would be his last election, win or lose. After [[Super Tuesday, 2008|Super Tuesday]] in 2008, Sanford received some mention as a potential running mate for the presumptive [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] presidential candidate, [[John McCain]].<ref>Holmes, Elizabeth. [http://online.wsj.com/public/article/SB120674979414973371-W6Qc_4E4VZiwFERnEM1YqPmQlX0_20080427.html?mod=tff_main_tff_top Delicate Proposal: McCain-Sanford]. ''The Wall Street Journal''. March 29, 2008. Page A4. Retrieved April 10, 2008.</ref><ref>[http://www.nbcnews.com/id/23209237/page/6/ 'Meet the Press' transcript for Feb 17, 2008]. ''NBC''. MSNBC. February 17, 2008. Retrieved April 10, 2008.</ref><ref>Cooper, Michael. [http://thecaucus.blogs.nytimes.com/2008/04/02/mccain-considering-vice-presidential-picks/ McCain Considering Vice President Picks]. ''The New York Times''. April 2, 2008. Retrieved April 10, 2008.</ref>\n\nSanford publicly aligned himself with McCain in a March 15, 2008, piece in the [[Wall Street Journal]]. Likening the presidential race to a [[American football|football]] game at halftime, Sanford noted that he \"sat out the first half, not endorsing a candidate...But I'm now stepping onto the field and going to work to help John McCain. It's important that conservatives do the same.\"<ref>{{cite news|first=Mark |last=Sanford |title=The Conservative Case for McCain |date=March 15, 2008 |publisher= |url=http://online.wsj.com/public/article_print/SB120553936399438277.html |work=[[Wall Street Journal]] |pages=A10 |accessdate=March 16, 2008 |language= |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080512015220/http://online.wsj.com/public/article_print/SB120553936399438277.html |archivedate=May 12, 2008 }}</ref>\n\nOn January 11, 2008, shortly before the South Carolina presidential primaries (R Jan 19, D Jan 26), Sanford published a guest column in the [[Columbia, South Carolina|Columbia]] newspaper ''The State''.<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.scgovernor.com/news/media/jan_11_2008.htm | work = The State | date = January 11, 2008 | title = Obama's symbolism here | first = Mark | last = Sanford | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20080111183735/http://www.scgovernor.com/news/media/jan_11_2008.htm | archive-date = January 11, 2008 | accessdate = April 4, 2016 }}</ref> In the article, \"Obama's Symbolism Here\", Sanford wrote, \"I won't be voting for Barack Obama for president\", but noted the \"historical burden\" borne by South Carolinians on the topic of race. He advised voters in South Carolina to take note of the symbolism of Obama's early success, with the knowledge that South Carolina was a segregated state less than fifty years earlier, and discouraged voting either for or against Obama on the basis of his race.\n\nOn a January 18, 2008 interview with [[CNN]]'s [[Wolf Blitzer]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://edition.cnn.com/TRANSCRIPTS/0801/18/sitroom.03.html |title=CNN.com \u2013 Transcripts |publisher=Edition.cnn.com |accessdate=July 25, 2012}}</ref> Sanford discussed his Obama article. Wolf Blitzer asked, \"Give us your mind-set. Why did you think it was so important to write this piece right now at this critical moment?\" Sanford responded, \"Well, it plays into a larger conversation that we're having as a family of South Carolinians on, in fact, the [constitutional] structure of our government.\" Also, Wolf Blitzer showed Sanford clips of recent comments made by John McCain and [[Mike Huckabee]] about the [[Confederate battle flag]] and asked Sanford, \"All right, two different positions, obviously. Who's right in this?\" Sanford responded, \"Well, it depends who you talk to.\" Sanford elaborated that \"if you were to talk to the vast majority of South Carolinians, they would say that we do not need to be debating where the Confederate flag is or is not.\"\n\nSanford attracted derision in the [[Liberalism in the United States|liberal]] [[blogosphere]] and among pundits and analysts on the left for a gaffe during an interview with CNN's Wolf Blitzer on July 13, 2008, when he had difficulty answering a question about differences between Senator McCain and incumbent President [[George W. Bush]] on economic policy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.charleston.net/news/2008/jul/15/sanford_fumbles_on_cnn47478/ |title=Sanford fumbles on CNN |publisher=Charleston.net |accessdate=July 25, 2012 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081122020657/http://www.charleston.net/news/2008/jul/15/sanford_fumbles_on_cnn47478/ |archivedate=November 22, 2008 }}</ref> \"I'm drawing a blank, and I hate when I do that, especially on television\", joked Sanford.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2008/07/13/mark-sanford-draws-a-blan_n_112391.html |title=Mark Sanford Draws A Blank On McCain/Bush Economics |publisher=Huffingtonpost.com |date= July 13, 2008|accessdate=July 25, 2012 |first=Nico |last=Pitney}}</ref>\n\n===Possible 2012 candidacy===\nAs early as January 2008, there had been anticipation that Sanford would run for [[United States presidential election, 2012|President in 2012]], and online support groups had sprung up on virtual social networks like [[Facebook]] in support of a Sanford ticket.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/group.php?gid=7511542695 |title=Mark Sanford for President 2012 |publisher=Facebook.com |accessdate=July 25, 2012 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091117174440/https://www.facebook.com/group.php?gid=7511542695 |archivedate=November 17, 2009 }}</ref><ref>[https://www.facebook.com/group.php?gid=33964867788 Mark Sanford President 2012] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091117174433/https://www.facebook.com/group.php?gid=33964867788 |date=November 17, 2009 }}</ref>\n\nFurther boosting Sanford's profile in advance of a potential candidacy, which at the time the governor neither ruled out nor expressly hinted at,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/blogs/politics/2009/02/gops-sanford-it/ |title=GOP's Sanford: It's Time to 'Rip the Band-Aid Off' |publisher=Blogs.abcnews.com |date=February 4, 2009 |accessdate=July 25, 2012}}</ref> he was elected as Chairman of the [[Republican Governors Association]] in November 2008<ref>[http://www.rga.org/default.asp?pt=newsdescr&RI=494 Republican Governors Announce Leadership] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081126201117/http://www.rga.org/default.asp?pt=newsdescr&RI=494 |date=November 26, 2008 }}</ref> and was cited by [[Michael S. Steele]], the Chairman of the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]] as one of four \"rising stars\" in the GOP (alongside Governors [[Bobby Jindal]] of [[Louisiana]], [[Tim Pawlenty]] of [[Minnesota]] and [[Sarah Palin]] of [[Alaska]]) in February 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/blogs/politics/2009/02/headline-to-com/ |title=GOP's Steele Touts Four Rising Stars |publisher=Blogs.abcnews.com |date=February 3, 2009 |accessdate=July 25, 2012}}</ref> Sanford also received early support for a presidential run from the [[Republican Liberty Caucus]].<ref>[http://rlcnews.org/?p=72 Republican Liberty Caucus Encourages Sanford to Run for President] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303195501/http://rlcnews.org/?p=72 |date=March 3, 2016 }}</ref>\n\nOn February 22, 2009, Sanford declined to rule out a possible presidential bid in 2012, though he professed to have no current plans to run for national office.<ref>[http://news.yahoo.com/s/ap/20090222/ap_on_go_pr_wh/governors2012;_ylt=As.HUk4MhvK9W08Kk2A3VyOyFz4D GOP governors don't say no to bids for president] {{dead link|date=May 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>\n\n''Washington Post'' blogger [[Chris Cillizza]] said that revelations of an extramarital affair in June 2009 ended Sanford's chances of being a serious candidate in 2012.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://voices.washingtonpost.com/thefix/governors/sanfords-admits-affair-first-t.html|title= Sanford Admits Affair, First Thoughts|last=Chris|first=Cillizza|date=June 24, 2009|work=[[Washington Post]]|accessdate=June 25, 2009}}</ref>\n\nOn January 4, 2010, Sanford admitted, \"If there's anything that's abundantly clear, it's that I ain't running for president.\" In the same Republican meeting, he also indicated that he would enter the private sector after his last 11 months as governor.<ref name=\"Island Packet\">{{cite web|last=McCann|first=Josh|url=http://www.islandpacket.com/2010/01/04/1089142/sanford-welcomed-monday-by-friendly.html|title=Sanford welcomed Monday by friendly crowd on Hilton Head Island|publisher=[[The Island Packet]]|location=Hilton Head Island; S.C.|date=January 4, 2010|accessdate=January 6, 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Post-gubernatorial career==\n[[File:Mark Sanford.jpg|right|thumb|Then-Governor Mark Sanford speaking at an event in September 2010.]]\nFollowing completion of his service as governor in January 2011, Sanford moved to his family farm in [[Beaufort County, South Carolina]], and later moved to a condominium in [[Charleston, South Carolina]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.postandcourier.com/article/20130110/PC16/130119908/1177/sanford-looking-at-potential-campaign-hq-space |title=Sanford looking at potential campaign HQ space |publisher=The Post and Courier article |date=January 10, 2013 |accessdate=May 1, 2013}}</ref> He has described this as a very quiet and spiritual time, and developed a Buddhist Christian life approach including a daily quiet time, practicing mindfulness, and emphasising everyone's 'shared human experience.'<ref>{{cite web|last=Zengerle |first=Jason |url=http://nymag.com/news/features/mark-sanford-2013-3/ |title=Former South Carolina Governor Mark Sanford Runs for Office Again \u2013 New York Magazine |publisher=Nymag.com |date=2013-03-03 |accessdate=2014-08-08}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=The Ticket |url=http://news.yahoo.com/blogs/ticket/mark-sanford-talks-buddhism-daily-meditation-practice-unique-000939600.html |title=Mark Sanford talks Buddhism, his daily meditation practice and unique campaign style &#124; The Ticket \u2013 Yahoo! News |publisher=News.yahoo.com |date=2013-05-06 |accessdate=2014-08-08}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2011, he was hired as a paid political contributor for [[Fox News Channel]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.abcnews4.com/story/15771358/former-sc-governor-to-join-fox-news |title=Former SC Governor to join Fox News team |publisher=Abcnews4.com |accessdate=July 25, 2012}}</ref> In August 2012, Sanford became engaged to his former mistress, Maria Belen Chapur.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.washingtonpost.com/national/former-sc-gov-sanford-confirms-engagement-to-ex-mistress-in-affair-that-ended-political-hopes/2012/08/26/2d1134f4-efa7-11e1-b74c-84ed55e0300b_story.html |title=Former SC Gov. Sanford confirms engagement to ex-mistress in affair that ended political hopes \u2013 The Washington Post |work=[[The Washington Post]] |date=August 26, 2012  |issn=0190-8286 |accessdate=August 26, 2012 |deadurl=yes}}{{dead link|date=May 2013}}</ref> The engagement was subsequently broken off in September, 2014.<ref name=\"postandcourier.com\"/><ref name=\"thestate.com\"/>\n\n==Return to the U.S. House of Representatives==\n\n===2013 Congressional special election===\n{{Main article|South Carolina's 1st congressional district special election, 2013}}\nIn December 2012, [[CNN]] reported that Sanford was considering a bid to retake his congressional seat. The previous holder, fellow Republican [[Tim Scott]], had been appointed to the [[United States Senate]] by Governor [[Nikki Haley]] after the resignation of Senator [[Jim DeMint]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://politicalticker.blogs.cnn.com/2012/12/20/first-on-cnn-mark-sanford-plans-to-run-for-congress/?iref=allsearch |title=FIRST ON CNN: Mark Sanford plans to run for Congress \u2013 CNN Political Ticker \u2013 CNN.com Blogs |publisher=Politicalticker.blogs.cnn.com |date=December 20, 2012 |accessdate=May 1, 2013}}</ref> On December 22, 2012, Sanford sent an email to supporters, confirming rumors that he intended to run for Congress in 2013.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.wsoctv.com/news/news/local/former-sc-governor-mark-sanford-run-congress/nTdfH/ |title=Former S.C. Governor Mark Sanford to run for Congress |work=[[WSOC-TV]]|date=December 23, 2012}}</ref>\n\nSanford formally launched his bid for Congress in early 2013. He quickly became a front-runner in a crowded field of 16 Republican candidates, because of his  name recognition.<ref>{{cite news|author=Karen Tumulty |url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/with-campaign-mark-sanford-goes-from-appalachian-trail-to-comeback-trail/2013/02/22/41a9bb7a-7d0a-11e2-a044-676856536b40_story.html |title=With House campaign, Mark Sanford goes from Appalachian Trail to comeback trail |publisher=The Washington Post |date=February 23, 2013 |accessdate=May 1, 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn April 2, 2013, Sanford won his Republican House primary runoff against Curtis Bostic, a former Charleston County councilman. The special election was held on May 7, 2013 and Sanford defeated [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]] Candidate [[Elizabeth Colbert Busch]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Cameron Joseph|title=Mark Sanford wins South Carolina House GOP primary runoff|url=http://thehill.com/blogs/ballot-box/house-races/291555-mark-sanford-wins-south-carolina-gop-primary|publisher=The Hill|accessdate=April 3, 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn April 17, 2013, the [[National Republican Congressional Committee]] pulled support from the Sanford campaign in the wake of revelations that Jenny Sanford had filed a trespassing complaint against him on February 4.<ref name=NRCCPull>Isenstadt, Mark. [http://www.politico.com/story/2013/04/mark-sanford-nrcc-90217.html Republicans pull plug on Mark Sanford]. [[Politico]], April 17, 2013.</ref> According to the complaint, Jenny Sanford had caught her former husband sneaking out of her home in Sullivan's Island, using his cellphone as a flashlight. Under the terms of their divorce agreement, neither Mark nor Jenny Sanford may come to the other's house without permission\u2014a condition Jenny Sanford alleged that Mark Sanford had flouted on numerous occasions despite Jenny Sanford filing a \"no trespass\" letter with the Sullivan's Island Police Department.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scribd.com/doc/136497668/Sanford-legal-documents |title=Trespassing complaint against Sanford |publisher=Scribd.com |date=April 17, 2013 |accessdate=May 1, 2013}}</ref> In a statement, Mark Sanford admitted that he'd gone to the house to watch the second half of [[Super Bowl XLVII]] with his son. He claimed to have tried to contact Jenny beforehand, but was unable to do so. Jenny Sanford filed the complaint the next morning. Several Republican operatives said that they were upset Sanford had known about this complaint for some time and failed to disclose it.<ref name=NRCCPull/>\n\nSanford was endorsed by [[FreedomWorks]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fitsnews.com/2013/04/30/freedomworks-backs-mark-sanford/ |title=SC-1: FreedomWorks Backs Mark Sanford |publisher=FITSNews |accessdate=May 1, 2013}}</ref> [[Governor of South Carolina|South Carolina Governor]] [[Nikki Haley]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/post-politics/wp/2013/04/29/nikki-haley-to-appear-at-mark-sanford-fundraiser/ |title=Nikki Haley to appear at Mark Sanford fundraiser |publisher=Washingtonpost.com |accessdate=May 1, 2013}}</ref> [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] and [[Speaker (politics)|House Speaker]] [[John Boehner]],<ref>{{cite web|last=Joseph |first=Cameron |url=http://thehill.com/blogs/ballot-box/house-races/292523-boehner-endorses-mark-sanford |title=Boehner endorses Mark Sanford in SC special election \u2013 The Hill's Ballot Box |publisher=Thehill.com |date=April 9, 2013 |accessdate=May 1, 2013}}</ref> [[South Carolina Senate|State Senator]] [[Tom Davis (South Carolina politician)|Tom Davis]],<ref>{{cite web|last=Drury |first=Shawn |url=http://northcharleston.patch.com/articles/sen-tom-davis-to-endorse-mark-sanford-in-sc1 |title=EXCLUSIVE: Sen. Tom Davis Endorses Mark Sanford in SC1 \u2013 North Charleston, SC Patch |publisher=Northcharleston.patch.com |date=January 25, 2013 |accessdate=May 1, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fitsnews.com/2013/02/12/tom-davis-endorses-mark-sanford/ |title=Tom Davis Endorses Mark Sanford |publisher=FITSNews |date=February 12, 2013 |accessdate=May 1, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Conley |first=Casey |url=http://www.islandpacket.com/2013/02/12/2377887/sen-tom-davis-endorses-mark-sanfords.html |title=Sen. Tom Davis endorses Mark Sanford's Congress comeback bid &#124; Election |publisher=The Island Packet |accessdate=May 1, 2013}}</ref> former [[State treasurer|South Carolina State Treasurer]] [[Thomas Ravenel]],<ref>{{cite web|last=Ravenel |first=Thomas |url=http://www.fitsnews.com/2013/04/01/t-rav-endorses-mark-sanford/ |title=T-Rav: My Endorsement Of Mark Sanford |publisher=FITSNews |date=April 1, 2013 |accessdate=May 1, 2013}}</ref> perennial candidate [[Ben Frasier]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/04/04/ben-frasier-mark-sanford_n_3015137.html |title=Ben Frasier Endorses Mark Sanford Over Former Rival Elizabeth Colbert Busch |publisher=Huffingtonpost.com |accessdate=May 1, 2013 |date=April 4, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Ould |first=Mohamedou |url=http://www.slate.com/blogs/weigel/2013/04/05/the_alvin_greene_scam_it_lives.html |title=The Alvin Greene Scam: It Lives! |publisher=Slate.com |date=April 5, 2013 |accessdate=May 1, 2013}}</ref> former [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] from [[Texas]] [[Ron Paul]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/04/25/ron-paul-mark-sanford_n_3157944.html |title=Ron Paul Endorses Mark Sanford, Because #YOLO |publisher=Huffingtonpost.com |date=April 25, 2013 |accessdate=May 1, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://redalertpolitics.com/2013/04/26/will-ron-paul-be-the-saving-grace-for-mark-sanfords-campaign/ |title=Will Ron Paul be the saving grace for Mark Sanford\u2019s campaign? |publisher=Redalertpolitics.com |date=April 26, 2013 |accessdate=May 1, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Alexis Levinson |url=http://dailycaller.com/2013/04/25/ron-paul-endorses-mark-sanford/ |title=Ron Paul endorses Mark Sanford |publisher=The Daily Caller |date=April 26, 2013 |accessdate=May 1, 2013}}</ref> and his son, [[United States Senate|U.S. Senator]] from [[Kentucky]] [[Rand Paul]].,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/04/30/rand-paul-mark-sanford_n_3186160.html |title=Rand Paul Endorses Mark Sanford In South Carolina Congressional Race |publisher=Huffingtonpost.com |accessdate=May 1, 2013 |date=April 30, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=Associated Press |url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/national/mark-sanford-elizabeth-colbert-busch-have-spirited-debate-in-sc-congressional-race/2013/04/29/f62fd4ae-b12a-11e2-9fb1-62de9581c946_story.html |title=After months of refusing to attack, Sanford\u2019s opponent puts him on the defensive over affair |publisher=The Washington Post |accessdate=May 1, 2013 |deadurl=yes}} {{Dead link|date=April 2014|bot=RjwilmsiBot}}</ref> and on May 1, 2013, [[United States Senate|U.S. Senator]] and former [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] [[Tim Scott]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/post-politics/wp/2013/05/01/tim-scott-endorses-mark-sanford/ |title=Tim Scott endorses Mark Sanford |publisher=Washingtonpost.com |date=January 1, 1970 |accessdate=May 2, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Joseph |first=Cameron |url=http://thehill.com/blogs/ballot-box/house-races/297289-tim-scott-endorses-mark-sanford-says-he-merits-support |title=Tim Scott endorses Mark Sanford, says he 'merits support' \u2013 The Hill's Ballot Box |publisher=Thehill.com |accessdate=May 2, 2013}}</ref> and [[United States Senate|U.S. Senator]] [[Lindsey Graham]]<ref>{{cite web|author=Igor Bobic 11:03 AM EDT, Wednesday May 1, 2013 |url=http://livewire.talkingpointsmemo.com/entry/lindsey-graham-endorses-mark-sanford-we-need-him |title=Lindsey Graham Endorses Mark Sanford: 'We Need Him In Washington' &#124; TPM LiveWire |publisher=Livewire.talkingpointsmemo.com |accessdate=May 2, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Alexis Levinson |url=http://dailycaller.com/2013/05/01/scott-graham-endorsements-give-boost-to-sanford-campaign/ |title=Scott, Graham endorsements give boost to Sanford campaign |publisher=The Daily Caller |date=April 26, 2013 |accessdate=May 2, 2013}}</ref> endorsed Sanford.\n\n[[Larry Flynt]] also endorsed him, saying \"His open embrace of his mistress in the name of love, breaking his sacred marriage vows, was an act of bravery that has drawn my support.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/04/30/larry-flynt-mark-sanford_n_3189201.html |title=Larry Flynt Endorses Mark Sanford, 'America's Great Sex Pioneer' |publisher=Huffingtonpost.com |accessdate=May 1, 2013 |first=Chris |last=Gentilviso |date=April 30, 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn May 7, 2013, Sanford was once again elected to the U.S. House of Representatives with 54.04% of the vote, defeating Elizabeth Colbert Busch.<ref>{{cite news|title=Mark Sanford wins South Carolina special election|url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/post-politics/wp/2013/05/07/mark-sanford-wins-south-carolina-special-election/|work=Washington Post|accessdate=May 8, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Statewide Results|url=http://www.enr-scvotes.org/SC/46180/116796/en/summary.html|publisher=South Carolina Dept. Of Elections|accessdate=May 8, 2013}}</ref>\n\nSanford was unopposed for re-election in 2014.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://onpolitics.usatoday.com/2014/03/31/once-disgraced-mark-sanford-is-now-unopposed/ |title=Once disgraced, Mark Sanford is unopposed |work=USA Today|date=March 31, 2014|accessdate=March 31, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Tenure===\nSanford was sworn-in on May 15, 2013.\n\nOn June 5, 2014, Sanford introduced the [[TSA Office of Inspection Accountability Act of 2014 (H.R. 4803; 113th Congress)]], a bill that would direct the [[Department of Homeland Security Office of Inspector General|Inspector General of the Department of Homeland Security]] (DHS) to review the data and methods that the [[Transportation Security Administration]] (TSA) uses to classify personnel as law enforcement officers and to reclassify, as necessary, any staff of the Office of Inspection that are currently misclassified according to the results of that review.<ref name=4803cbo>{{cite web|title=CBO \u2013 H.R. 4803|url=http://www.cbo.gov/publication/45489|publisher=Congressional Budget Office|accessdate=23 July 2014}}</ref> Sanford said that \"even though there are federal standards in place that lay out how employees qualify for higher wages, the Transportation Security Administration pays some of their employees more for jobs they're not doing. That wouldn't make sense anywhere outside of government and our bill would help fix that problem by clarifying those employees' responsibilities.\"<ref name=HStodayJuly23>{{cite news|title=House Passes Legislation On Transportation Security|url=http://www.hstoday.us/industry-news/general/single-article/house-passes-legislation-on-transportation-security/b3c18799bd39d2eb088242a7b436c50d.html|accessdate=24 July 2014|publisher=Homeland Security Today|date=23 July 2014}}</ref> According to Sanford, accurately reclassifying employees who do not spent at least 50 percent of the time on law enforcement activities and putting them on an accurate pay scale would save the government $17 million a year.<ref name=FedTimesJuly23>{{cite news|last1=Medici|first1=Andy|title=House passes bill to demote some TSA officers|url=http://www.federaltimes.com/article/20140723/BENEFITS/307230011/House-passes-bill-demote-some-TSA-officers?odyssey=nav%7Chead|accessdate=24 July 2014|publisher=Federal Times|date=23 July 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Committee assignments===\n*'''[[United States House Committee on the Budget|Committee on the Budget]]'''\n*'''[[United States House Committee on Homeland Security|Committee on Homeland Security]]'''<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.postandcourier.com/article/20130606/PC16/130609474/1009/rep-mark-sanford-gets-2-committee-assignments|title=Rep. Mark Sanford gets 2 committee assignments|publisher=The Post and Courier|date=6 June 2013|accessdate=6 June 2013}}</ref>\n** [[United States House Homeland Security Subcommittee on Emergency Preparedness, Response, and Communications|Subcommittee on Emergency Preparedness, Response, and Communications]]\n** [[United States House Homeland Security Subcommittee on Transportation Security|Subcommittee on Transportation Security]]\n*'''[[United States House Committee on Transportation and Infrastructure|Committee on Transportation and Infrastructure]]'''\n** [[United States House Transportation Subcommittee on Coast Guard and Maritime Transportation|Subcommittee on Coast Guard and Maritime Transportation]]\n** [[United States House Transportation Subcommittee on Economic Development, Public Buildings and Emergency Management|Subcommittee on Economic Development, Public Buildings and Emergency Management]]\n** [[United States House Transportation Subcommittee on Water Resources and Environment|Subcommittee on Water Resources and Environment]]\n\n===Caucus memberships===\n* [[Liberty Caucus]]\n* [[Freedom Caucus]].<ref>{{cite web| url= http://fivethirtyeight.com/datalab/the-hard-line-republicans-who-pushed-john-boehner-out/ | first1= Carl |last1=Bialik |first2=Aaron|last2= Bycoffe | title= The Hard-Line Republicans Who Pushed John Boehner Out | date= 25 September 2015 | work= [[FiveThirtyEight]]| access-date= 2015-09-28}}</ref>\n\n==Books==\nIn 2000 Sanford's first book, ''The Trust Committed To Me'', was published. It discussed [[term limit]]s, and featured a foreword by [[Robert Novak]].<ref>\n{{cite book|title=The Trust Committed to Me|first=Mark|last=Sanford|publisher=U.S. Term Limits Foundation|year=2000|isbn=0-9638615-1-4|location=Washington, D.C.}}</ref> A second book, titled ''Within Our Means'', was scheduled to be published by [[Sentinel HC|Sentinel]] in 2010: however the contract was terminated by mutual agreement after the revelation of Sanford's extramarital affair.<ref>\n{{cite news|title=Sentinel Kills Sanford Book|first=Rachel|last=Deahl|work=Publishers Weekly|date=July 2, 2009|url=http://www.publishersweekly.com/article/CA6668797.html?industryid=47146}}</ref>\n\nHe is also the subject of a book by his longtime [[speechwriter]], Barton Swaim, titled ''The Speechwriter: A Brief Education in Politics''.\n\n==Electoral history==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin:0.5em ; font-size:95%\"\n|+ {{ushr|South Carolina|1|}}: results 1994\u20132013<ref name=\"clerkresults\">{{cite web|url=http://clerk.house.gov/member_info/electionInfo/index.html |title=Election Statistics |accessdate=January 10, 2008 |publisher=Office of the Clerk of the House of Representatives |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080730201058/http://clerk.house.gov/member_info/electionInfo/index.html |archivedate=July 30, 2008 |df=mdy }}</ref>\n!|Year\n!\n!|Democrat\n!|Votes\n!|Pct\n!\n!|Republican\n!|Votes\n!|Pct\n!\n!|3rd party\n!|Party\n!|Votes\n!|Pct\n!\n|-\n|[[U.S. House election, 1994|1994]]\n|\n|{{Party shading/Democratic}} |[[Robert A. Barber, Jr.]]\n|{{Party shading/Democratic}} align=\"right\" |47,769\n|{{Party shading/Democratic}} |32%\n|\n|{{Party shading/Republican}} |{{nowrap|'''Mark Sanford'''}}\n|{{Party shading/Republican}} align=\"right\" |97,803\n|{{Party shading/Republican}} |66%\n|\n|{{Party shading/Libertarian}} |Robert Payne\n|{{Party shading/Libertarian}} |[[Libertarian Party (United States)|Libertarian]]\n|{{Party shading/Libertarian}} align=\"right\" |1,836\n|{{Party shading/Libertarian}} align=\"right\" |1%\n| |'''*'''\n|-\n|[[U.S. House election, 1996|1996]]\n|\n|{{Party shading/Democratic}} |''(no candidate)''\n|{{Party shading/Democratic}} align=\"right\" |\n|{{Party shading/Democratic}} |\n|\n|{{Party shading/Republican}} |'''Mark Sanford'''\n|{{Party shading/Republican}} align=\"right\" |138,467\n|{{Party shading/Republican}} |96%\n|\n|! style=\"background:#00bfff; \"|Joseph F. Innella\n|! style=\"background:#00bfff; \"|[[Natural Law Party (United States)|Natural Law]]\n|!  style=\"background:#00bfff; text-align:right;\"|5,105\n|!  style=\"background:#00bfff; text-align:right;\"|4%\n|\n|-\n|[[U.S. House election, 1998|1998]]\n|\n|{{Party shading/Democratic}} |''(no candidate)''\n|{{Party shading/Democratic}} align=\"right\" |\n|{{Party shading/Democratic}} |\n|\n|{{Party shading/Republican}} |'''Mark Sanford'''\n|{{Party shading/Republican}} align=\"right\" |118,414\n|{{Party shading/Republican}} |91%\n|\n|! style=\"background:#00bfff; \"|Joseph F. Innella\n|! style=\"background:#00bfff; \"|[[Natural Law Party (United States)|Natural Law]]\n|!  style=\"background:#00bfff; text-align:right;\"|11,586\n|!  style=\"background:#00bfff; text-align:right;\"|9%\n| |'''*'''\n|-\n|[[United States elections, 2013|2013]]\n|